snippet.textDisplay: Ramen-with-eggs pro tip: If you boil an egg while you're boiling the noodles, you can end up with a jammy egg like you'd have in an actual ramen restaurant. The egg (if you're taking it out of the fridge and it's extra cold) probably needs like 4.5-5 min to boil or else it will be a little under done, and peeling it can be kind of a pain, but imo it's totally worth it. Also if you're making microwave noodles you can break an egg into the bowl after adding water and before heating, then heat for 4 min and you'll also end up with a delicious jammy egg.
snippet.textOriginal: Ramen-with-eggs pro tip: If you boil an egg while you're boiling the noodles, you can end up with a jammy egg like you'd have in an actual ramen restaurant. The egg (if you're taking it out of the fridge and it's extra cold) probably needs like 4.5-5 min to boil or else it will be a little under done, and peeling it can be kind of a pain, but imo it's totally worth it. Also if you're making microwave noodles you can break an egg into the bowl after adding water and before heating, then heat for 4 min and you'll also end up with a delicious jammy egg.
